## EDA Conclusions

This exploratory analysis examined financial survey responses to understand how demographic characteristics influence investment behavior and financial decision-making.

Respondents of both genders demonstrate strong interest in investing and show similar investment preferences. 
Investment preferences are relatively similar for males of different age, while for women it differs more with young age.
With regard to their investment goals, wealth creation is the dominant investment objective for both genders prioritizing a balance between return expectations and risk considerations. 
Popular response of monthly checking on investments indicates a moderate engagement from the reposindents.
Surprisingly, a retirement contributions was revealed to be important among all respondents, which age is span between 21 and 35. This, 
together with monthly engagements and balanced risks indicate an opportunity to engage more customers offering related fincancial products.

Although the dataset is relatively small, the results illustrate how survey data can be used to explore behavioral patterns in personal finance and investment preferences.

